item.title: Sample Page
item.dc:creator: user
item.content:encoded:
This is an example page. It's different from a blog post because it will stay in one place and will show up in your site navigation (in most themes). Most people start with an About page that introduces them to potential site visitors. It might say something like this:

Hi there! I'm a bike messenger by day, aspiring actor by night, and this is my website. I live in Los Angeles, have a great dog named Jack, and I like piña coladas. (And gettin' caught in the rain.)

...or something like this:

The XYZ Doohickey Company was founded in 1971, and has been providing quality doohickeys to the public ever since. Located in Gotham City, XYZ employs over 2,000 people and does all kinds of awesome things for the Gotham community.

As a new WordPress user, you should go to your dashboard to delete this page and create new pages for your content. Have fun!

item.title: Submission
item.dc:creator: ahi620
item.content:encoded:
OBA Submission form

GA 1

A Knowledgebase for Engineering Demonstrated competence in university-level mathematics, natural sciences, engineering fundamentals, and specialized engineering knowledge appropriate to the program.

1.1:  Create mathematical expressions to describe physical phenomena (or a physical problem).
1.2:  Select and describe appropriate tools to solve mathematical problems that arise from modelling physical phenomena.
1.3:  Use solutions to mathematical problems to inform the (real-world problem) that gave rise to it.
1.4:  Identify fundamental scientific and engineering principles that govern the performance of a given process or system.
1.5:  Recall and describe fundamental concepts in natural sciences.

GA 2

An ability to use appropriate knowledge and skills to identify, formulate, analyze, and solve complex engineering problems in order to reach substantiated conclusions.

2.1:  Create processes for solving problems including justified approximations and assumptions.
2.2:  Evaluate the validity of results and model for error/uncertainty.
2.3:  Reframe complex problems into interconnected sub-problems, using a systems approach.
2.4:  Identify known and unknown information, uncertainties, and biases in complex ill-structured problems.

GA 3

An ability to conduct investigations of complex problems by methods that include appropriate experiments, analysis and interpretation of data, and synthesis of information in order to reach valid conclusions.

3.1:  Generate working hypotheses and assumptions for engineering problems.
3.2:  Develop investigations involving information and data gathering, analysis, and/or experimentation.
3.3:  Analyze and interpret data and information to reach a conclusion using a systems approach.
3.4:  Identify limitations of the tests and methods used and their impact on the results.

GA 4

An ability to design solutions for complex, open-ended engineering problems and to design systems, components or processes that meet specified needs with appropriate attention to health and safety risks, applicable standards, and economic, environmental, cultural and societal considerations.

4.1:  Follow a general procedure to design a system, component, or process for a complex open-ended problem.
4.2: Identity client and user needs.
4.3:  Evaluate the design options against project criteria using a systems approach.
4.4:  Assess design based on requirements, yield, reliability, safety, and impact on environment and society.
4.5:  Create and test simulations, models, and/or prototypes of the design.
4.6:  Incorporate client/user feedback into the design.

GA 5

An ability to create, select, apply, adapt, and extend appropriate techniques, resources, and modern engineering tools to a range of engineering activities, from simple to complex, with an understanding of the associated limitations.

5.1:  Select appropriate measurement devices or techniques to accomplish a task.
5.2:  Demonstrate correct usage of testing apparatus, databases, models, and/or standards.
5.3  Analyze the limitations, uncertainties, and sources of error inherent in engineering tools.
5.4:  Evaluate the appropriateness of results from instrumentation, measurements techniques, models and simulations.

GA 6

An ability to work effectively as a member and leader in teams, preferably in a multi-disciplinary setting.

6.1:  Assume personal responsibility for one's own work and collective accountability for the teamwork.
6.2:  Apply principles of conflict management and personal accountability.
6.3:  Evaluate team effectiveness and plans for improvement.
6.4:  Report results as a team, with contributions from all individual efforts.

GA 7

An ability to communicate complex engineering concepts within the profession and with society at large. Such ability includes reading, writing, speaking and listening, and the ability to comprehend and write effective reports and design documentation, and to give and effectively respond to clear instructions.

7.1:  Write technical documentation using standard formats, grammar, and mechanics.
7.2:  Utilize proper referencing and citations in written works.
7.3:  Deliver clear and organized formal presentations.
7.4: Create figures, tables and graphics to engineering report standards.
7.5:  Uses a suitable format for a technical report.

GA 8

An understanding of the roles and responsibilities of the professional engineer in society, especially the primary role of protection of the public and the public interest.

8.1:  Recognize protection of the public and public interest in decision making and recommendations.
8.2:  Identify relevant engineering professional and technical organizations.
8.3:  Demonstrate awareness of engineering as a regulated profession, including reference to relevant engineering regulations/codes/standards.
8.4:  Demonstrates accountability through performance (meets deadlines, submits quality work, adheres to requirements, etc.).

GA 9

An ability to analyze social and environmental aspects of engineering activities. Such ability includes an understanding of the interactions that engineering has with the economic, social, health, safety, legal, and cultural aspects of society, the uncertainties in the prediction of such interactions; and the concepts of sustainable design and development and environmental stewardship.

9.1:  Compare technological alternatives and identify means to mitigate social, environmental, human health and safety impacts.
9.2:  Balance economic, cultural, societal and technical considerations.
9.3:  Apply principles of preventive engineering, life cycle analysis, and sustainable development.

GA 10

An ability to apply professional ethics, accountability, and equity.

10.1:  Adhere to the principles of academic and professional integrity.
10.2:  Describe ethical and equity issues and how they affect the individual, organization and the public.
10.3:  Understand consequences of deviating from professional and organizational codes of conduct.
10.4:  Comprehend and demonstrate sensitivity to cultural and gender issues.

GA 11

An ability to appropriately incorporate economics and business practices including project, risk and change management into the practice of engineering and to understand their limitations.

11.1:  Define the project scope, tasks, milestones, and/or required resources.
11.2:  Determine whether the project is economically viable and attractive.
11.3:  Comprehend, evaluate, and manage risk.
11.4:  Plan and schedule a project to bring it in on time and resources.
11.5:  Outline a quality assurance plan for project management.
11.6:  Recognize the various types of benefits, costs, and risks in a projects life cycle.

GA 12

An ability to identify and to address their own educational needs in a changing world in ways sufficient to maintain their competence and to allow them to contribute to the advancement of knowledge.

12.1:  Identify how new knowledge enters the discipline via scholarly and industry-related sources.
12.2:  Recognize the requirements for maintaining professional registration and/or licensing.
12.3:  Identify deficiencies or gaps of one's understanding and knowledge.
12.4:  Evaluate information for authenticity, currency and objectivity.
